==Foreign relations and military==
{{Main|Foreign relations of Afghanistan|Military of Afghanistan}}
[[File:US Embassy in Kabul on July 4th 2010.jpg|thumb|The [[U.S. Embassy, Kabul|U.S. Embassy in Kabul]]. Official [[Afghanistan <U+2013> United States relations|diplomatic relations between the United States and Afghanistan]] began in the early 1920s. The [[United States Department of State]] is currently planning to establish a [[Consul (representative)|consulate]] in [[Herat]] in the west, [[Mazar-e-Sharif]] in the north, [[Kandahar]] in the south, and [[Jalalabad]] in the east.]]
The [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] is responsible for managing the [[foreign relations of Afghanistan]]. The nation has been a member of the UN since 1946, and has maintained good [[Afghanistan <U+2013> United States relations|relations with the United States]] and other [[NATO]] member states since the early 1920s.{{Citation needed|date=July 2011}} In 2002, the [[United Nations Assistance Mission in Afghanistan]] was established to help with assistance. Today, more than 22 NATO nations deploy about 140,000 troops in Afghanistan as part of the [[International Security Assistance Force]] (ISAF). Apart from close military links, Afghanistan also enjoys strong economic relations with NATO members and their allies.
[[File:NMAA June 2010.jpg|thumb|left|Cadets and instructors at the [[National Military Academy of Afghanistan]] (NMAA).]]

Afghanistan also has diplomatic relations with neighboring Pakistan, [[Afghanistan<U+2013>Iran relations|Iran]], [[Turkmenistan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[Tajikistan]], the [[People's Republic of China]], including regional states [[Kazakhstan]], Russia, India, [[United Arab Emirate]], Saudi Arabia, Iraq, Egypt, Japan, South Korea, and others. Afghanistan's [[Afghanistan<U+2013>Pakistan relations|relationship with Pakistan]] have often fluctuated since 1947.<ref>Hasnat, Syed Farooq, "Pakistan & Afghanistan: Domestic Pressures and Regional Threats" in Journal of International Affairs, Vol. 63, Fall/Winter 2009, pp. 141<U+2013>55, Columbia University [http://jia.sipa.columbia.edu/pakistan%E2%80%99s-strategic-interests-afghanistan-and-fluctuating-us-strategy link] ''"Since 1947, serious differences and tensions have existed between the two respective governments at various phases of Pakistan-Afghanistan relations."''</ref><ref>[http://www.usip.org/resources/resolving-pakistan-afghanistan-stalemate Resolving the Pakistan<U+2013>Afghanistan Stalemate], United States Institute of Peace, ''Afghanistan and Pakistan have had largely antagonistic relations under all governments''</ref> They have security and economic links with each others but disputes between the two states remain. Afghanistan continues to contest the [[Durrand Line]] as its international border with Pakistan,<ref name="FG">{{cite web |url=http://www.carnegieendowment.org/files/cp72_grare_final.pdf |title=Carnegie Papers <U+2013> Pakistan-Afghanistan Relations in the Post-9/11 Era |publisher= |first=Fr<U+00E9>d<U+00E9>ric |last=Grare |date=October 2006 |accessdate=2011-02-11}}</ref> and has repeatedly accused Pakistan of supporting Taliban and other insurgent groups.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.hurriyet.com.tr/english/world/9387172.asp?gid=244&sz=48187 |title=Afghan officials accuse Pakistan of embassy attack |publisher=Hurriyet |date=  |accessdate=July 13, 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2006/12/12/AR2006121200194.html |title=Pakistan Accused of Supporting Taliban |publisher=Washington Post |date= December 12, 2006 |accessdate=July 13, 2011 }}</ref> Pakistan harbors concerns over the [[Afghanistan<U+2013>India relations|growing influence]] of its rival India in Afghanistan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cic.nyu.edu/afghanistan/docs/stalemate.pdf |title=Resolving the Pakistan-Afghanistan Stalemate |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> Relations between the two states were strained further after recent [[Afghanistan<U+2013>Pakistan skirmishes|border skirmishes]] and when Afghan officials alleged that Pakistani intelligence agencies are involved in terrorist attacks inside Afghanistan.<ref name="dawn.com">{{cite web|url=http://www.dawn.com/wps/wcm/connect/dawn-content-library/dawn/news/world/13+pakistan+stoking+violence+in+afghanistan+adviser-za-01 |title=World &#124; Pakistan stoking violence in Afghanistan: adviser |publisher=Dawn.Com |date=October 15, 2009 |accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> Despite these problems, Pakistan is a participant in the reconstruction of Afghanistan, pledging $250 million in various projects across the country,<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://thepeopleofpakistan.wordpress.com/2010/07/12/pakistan-afghanistan-the-conjoined-twins/ |title=Pakistan-Afghanistan: The Conjoined Twins |publisher=Thepeopleofpakistan.wordpress.com |date=July 12, 2010 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> and often announces that a stable Afghanistan is in their interest.<ref>[http://www.pajhwok.com/en/2011/08/02/stable-afghanistan-interest-region-zardari Stable Afghanistan in the interest of region: Zardari]. Wasim Yousufzai. August 2, 2011.</ref>

India and Iran have actively participated in reconstruction efforts in Afghanistan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://reliefweb.int/rw/RWFiles2009.nsf/FilesByRWDocUnidFilename/VVOS-7Y4RBQ-full_report.pdf/$File/full_report.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5neRkSkWj|archivedate=February 19, 2010 |title=Engaging regional players in Afghanistan |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> with India being the largest regional donor to the country.<ref name=BBC1>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/mobile/world-south-asia-13370637|title=Indian PM Manmohan Singh pledges $500m to Afghanistan |date=12 May 11 |accessdate=13 July 11}}</ref> Since 2002, India has pledged up to $2 billion in economic assistance to Afghanistan and has participated in multiple socio-economic reconstruction efforts, including power, roads, agricultural and educational projects.<ref name=BBC1/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.forbes.com/2009/11/23/india-afghanistan-manmohan-singh-opinions-contributors-mumbai.html |title=We Need India's Help In Afghanistan |publisher=Forbes.com |date=November 23, 2009 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> There are also limited military ties between the two nations as some Afghan security forces are getting counter-insurgency training in India.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stratfor.com/analysis/afghanistan_why_india_s_cooperation_problem_pakistan |title=Afghanistan: Why India's Cooperation is a Problem for Pakistan |publisher=Stratfor.com |date=April 11, 2008 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Sujan Dutta |url=http://www.telegraphindia.com/1091204/jsp/frontpage/story_11820686.jsp |title=US feelers on Afghan army <U+2013> Admiral sounds India on training |publisher=Telegraphindia.com |date=December 4, 2009 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref>

The [[military of Afghanistan]] is under the [[Ministry of Defense (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Defense]], which includes the [[Afghan National Army]] and the [[Afghan National Army Air Force]]. It currently has about 160,000 members and is expected to reach 260,000 in the coming years.<ref name=Pellerindate/> They are trained and equipped by NATO countries, mainly by the [[United States Department of Defense]]. The ANA is divided into 7 major [[Corps]], with the [[201st Corps (Afghanistan)|201st Selab ("Flood")]] in Kabul being the main one. The ANA also has a [[ANA Commando Brigade|commando brigade]] which was established in 2007. The [[National Military Academy of Afghanistan]] serves as the main educational institute for the militarymen of the country. A new $200 million [[Afghan Defense University]] (ADU) is under construction near the capital.

==Economy==
{{Main|Economy of Afghanistan}}
[[File:Afghan pomegranate processing.jpg|thumb|Workers processing [[pomegranate production in Afghanistan|pomegranate]]s (''anaar''), which Afghanistan is famous for in Asia.]]
Afghanistan is an impoverished and [[least developed country]], one of the world's poorest. In 2010, the nation's nominal GDP stood at $16.63 billion and the [[List of countries by GDP (PPP) per capita|GDP per capita]] was about $1,000.<ref name=CIA-GDP-PPP>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2004.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af |title=GDP <U+2013> per capita (PPP): $1,000 (2010 est.)|work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> Its unemployment rate is 35%<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2129.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af |title=35% (2008 est.)|work=The World Factbook|publisher=Central Intelligence Agency|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> and roughly 36% of its citizens live below the poverty line.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2046.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af |title=36% (FY08/09) |work=The World Factbook|publisher=CIA|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> About 42 percent of the population live on less than $1 a day, according to USAID.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=83417|title=Afghanistan: Food still unaffordable for millions|work=|publisher=[[IRIN]]|date=March 12, 2009|accessdate=October 11, 2010}}</ref> However, due to the infusion of multi-billion dollars in international assistance and investments, as well as remittances from expats, the economy has steadily improving, growing at approximately 12 percent per year during the past six years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov//en/Page.CountryOverview.aspx |title=USAID/Afghanistan Strategy |work=|publisher=USAID|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref> It is also due to improvements in [[Ministry of Agriculture, Irrigation & Livestock (Afghanistan)|agricultural production]], which is the backbone of the nation's economy because over 75% of its citizens are involved in this field.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Program.19c.aspx |title=Objective: Accelerating market-led growth in agriculture|work=|publisher=USAID|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}{{dead link|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov/en/Program.19c.aspx|date=May 2011}}</ref>
[[File:Doost Marble Factory in Herat.jpg|thumb|left|The Doost Marble Factory in [[Herat]]. Current marble exports are estimated at $15 million per year. With improved extraction, processing, infrastructure, and investment, the industry has the potential to grow into a $450 million per year business.<ref>[[U.S. Embassy, Kabul]], [http://www.flickr.com/photos/usaidafghanistan/sets/72157626680123295/with/5759030503/ Third Afghanistan Marble Conference, May 25, 2011].</ref>]]
[[File:Bazaar Scene of Kabul.jpg|thumb|Local market scene in 2007]]
One of the main drivers for the current economic recovery is the return of over 5 million [[Afghan diaspora|Afghan expatriates]], who brought with them fresh energy, entrepreneurship and wealth-creating skills as well as much needed funds to start up businesses. A number of small factories began operating in different parts of the country in recent years, which not only provide revenue to the government but also create jobs. The [[Afghan rug]]s have become a popular product again and this gives the large number of rug weavers in the country a chance to earn better income. While the country's current account deficit is largely financed with the donor money, only a small portion is provided directly to the government budget. The rest is provided to non-budgetary expenditure and donor-designated projects through the United Nations system and non-governmental organizations.

The [[Ministry of Finance (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Finance]] is focusing on improved revenue collection and public sector expenditure discipline. Since 2003, over 16 new banks have opened in the country, including [[Afghanistan International Bank]], [[Kabul Bank]], [[Azizi Bank]], [[Pashtany Bank]], [[Standard Chartered Bank]], [[First Micro Finance Bank]], and others. [[Da Afghanistan Bank]] serves as the central bank of the nation and the [[Afghan afghani|"Afghani"]] (AFN) is the national currency, with an exchange rate of 50 Afghanis to 1 US dollar.

Afghanistan is a member of the [[South Asian Association for Regional Cooperation|SAARC]], [[Economic Cooperation Organization|ECO]] and the [[Economy of the OIC|OIC]]. It is known for producing some of the finest [[pomegranate]]s, grapes, apricots, melons, and several other fresh and dry fruits, including nuts.<ref>[http://www.ipsnews.net/news.asp?idnews=49291 Exporting Afghanistan], by P.J. Tobia. Nov 17, 2009.</ref> According to the [[World Bank]], "economic growth has been strong and has generated better livelihoods" since late 2001.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://web.worldbank.org/WBSITE/EXTERNAL/COUNTRIES/SOUTHASIAEXT/EXTSAREGTOPPOVRED/0,,contentMDK:20574056~menuPK:493447~pagePK:34004173~piPK:34003707~theSitePK:493441,00.html |title=Poverty Reduction <U+2013> Poverty in Afghanistan |publisher=Web.worldbank.org |date= |accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> [[Opium production in Afghanistan]] has soared to a record in 2007 with about 3 million Afghans reported to be involved in the business<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/afghanistan/story/0,,2157313,00.html UN horrified by surge in opium trade in Helmand].</ref> but then declined significantly in the years following.<ref>[http://www.unodc.org/unodc/en/frontpage/2009/September/afghan-opium-production-in-significant--decline.html Afghan opium production in significant decline], [[UNDOC]]</ref> The government started programs to help reduce cultivation of poppy, and by 2010 it was reported that 24 out of the 34 provinces were free from poppy grow.

===Energy and mining===
{{Main|Mining in Afghanistan}}
According to recent U.S. Geological surveys that were funded by the [[Council of Ministers (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Mines and Industry]], Afghanistan may be possessing up to {{convert|36|Tcuft|km3}} of natural gas, {{convert|3.6|Goilbbl|m3}} of petroleum and up to {{convert|1325|Moilbbl|m3}} of [[natural gas liquids]].<ref name="Eurasianet">[http://www.eurasianet.org/departments/insight/articles/eav090306.shtml ''Afghanistan<U+2019>s Energy Future and its Potential Implications''], Eurasianet.org.</ref> Other recent reports show that the country has huge amounts of gold, copper, coal, iron ore and other [[minerals]].<ref name="mom">{{cite web|url=http://www.mom.gov.af/uploads/files/English/USGS%20Report/8.0-chemical-sedimentry-FINAL.pdf |title=8.0 Chemical-sedimentary deposits |format=PDF |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref><ref name="bgs">{{cite web |url=http://www.bgs.ac.uk/AfghanMinerals/docs/Gold_A4.pdf#search='gold%20and%20copper%20discovered%20in%20afghanistan' |title=Minerals in Afghanistan |publisher=[[British Geological Survey]] |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref><ref name="uranium">{{cite web |url=http://www.wise-uranium.org/uissr05.html#OPER |title=Uranium Mining Issues: 2005 Review |publisher=Wise Uranium Project |accessdate=December 4, 2010}}</ref><ref name="Afghanistan's Mineral Fortune">{{cite web |url=http://www.uvm.edu/ieds/node/568/ |title=Afghanistan's Mineral Fortune |format=pdf | publisher=Institute for Environmental Diplomacy and Security Report |year=2011}}</ref> In 2010, [[The Pentagon|Pentagon]] officials along with geologists from the United States announced the discovery of $1<U+2013>3 trillion worth untapped mineral deposits in Afghanistan.<ref name="NYT" /> Afghan officials assert that "this will become the backbone of the Afghan economy" and a memo from the Pentagon stated that Afghanistan could become the "Saudi Arabia of [[lithium]]".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.discovery.com/earth/afghanistan-minerals-lithium.html |title=Afghanistan: The Saudi Arabia of Lithium? |publisher=News.discovery.com |date=June 14, 2010 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ksdk.com/news/local/story.aspx?storyid=204154 |title=Afghanistan is suddenly wealthy: US finds $1 trillion in mineral deposits |publisher=Ksdk.com |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/afghanistans-resources-could-make-it-the-richest-mining-region-on-earth-2000507.html |title=Afghanistan's resources could make it the richest mining region on earth |publisher=Independent.co.uk |date= June 15, 2010|accessdate=November 14, 2010 |location=London |first=Kim |last=Sengupta}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://business.timesonline.co.uk/tol/business/industry_sectors/natural_resources/article7149696.ece|location=London|work=The Times|title=Taleban zones mineral riches may rival Saudi Arabia says Pentagon|first1=Jeremy|last1=Page|first2=Michael|last2=Evans|date=June 15, 2010}}</ref> The government is preparing deals to extract its copper and iron reserves, which could earn billions of dollars in royalties and taxes every year for the next 100 years. Analysts believe that if the Afghan state was to generate even $10 billion per year from its mineral deposits, its gross national product would double and provide long-term funding for Afghan security forces and other critical needs.<ref>O'Hanlon, Michael E. [http://www.brookings.edu/opinions/2010/0616_afghanistan_minerals_ohanlon.aspx "Deposits Could Aid Ailing Afghanistan"], [http://www.brookings.edu/ The Brookings Institution], 16 June 2010.</ref>

===Transport and communications===
{{Main|Transport in Afghanistan|Communications in Afghanistan}}
[[File:Ariana Afghan A310-300 F-GEMO.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Ariana Afghan Airlines]]]]
[[Ariana Afghan Airlines]] is the national carrier, with domestic flights between Kabul, Kandahar, Herat and Mazar-i-Sharif. International flights include to [[Dubai]], Frankfurt, [[Istanbul]] and a number of other Asian destinations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://flyariana.com/schedules.php# |title=Ariana |publisher=Flyariana.com |date= |accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> There are also limited domestic and international flight services available from the locally owned [[Kam Air]], [[Pamir Airways]] and [[Safi Airways]].

The country has [[Rail transport in Afghanistan|limited rail service]] with Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan in the north. As of 2011, two other railway projects are in progress with neighboring nations, one is between Herat and Iran while another is to connect with [[Pakistan Railways]]. Citizens who travel far distances use bus services. Newer automobiles have recently become more widely available after the rebuilding of roads and highways. Vehicles are imported from the [[United Arab Emirates]] through Pakistan and Iran. [[Postage stamps and postal history of Afghanistan|Afghanistan's postal]] and package delivery services such as [[FedEx]], [[DHL]] and others are found in major cities and towns.

Telecommunication services in the country are provided by [[Afghan Wireless]], [[Etisalat]], [[Roshan (telco)|Roshan]], [[MTN Group]] and [[Afghan Telecom]]. In 2006, the [[Ministry of Communications (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Communications]] signed a $64.5 million agreement with [[ZTE]] for the establishment of a countrywide [[optical fiber cable]] network. As of 2009, the country has 129,300 fixed telephone lines,<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2150.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af CIA.gov]</ref> about 12 million mobile phone subscribers<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2151.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af CIA.Gov]</ref> and 1 million internet users.<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2153.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af CIA.gov]</ref>

==Demographics==
{{Main|Demography of Afghanistan|Afghan refugees}}
As of July 2010, the population of Afghanistan is around 28,395,716,<ref name="CIA-pop">{{cite web| url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2119.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas&#af|title=Population of Afghanistan |work=The World Factbook |publisher=CIA |year=2010|accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> but it is unknown if the 3 million [[Afghan refugees]] living in [[Afghans in Pakistan|Pakistan]] and [[Afghans in Iran|Iran]] are included or not. A 2009 UN estimate shows that the Afghan population was 28,150,000<ref name=unpop>{{Cite journal| url=http://www.un.org/esa/population/publications/wpp2008/wpp2008_text_tables.pdf | title=World Population Prospects, Table A.1 |version=2008 revision|format=PDF|publisher=United Nations |work=Department of Economic and Social Affairs Population Division |year=2009 |accessdate=March 12, 2009}}</ref> and a 2009<U+2013>2010 nationwide [[statistical survey]] conducted by the [[Central Statistics Office (Afghanistan)|Central Statistics Office]] (CSO) of Afghanistan has put it at 26 million but not counting some parts of the country due to insecurity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pajhwok.com/viewstory.asp?lng=eng&id=99681 |title=CSO census puts population at 26 million |accessdate=August 16, 2010 |work=Rahmatullah Afghan |publisher=Pajhwok Afghan News |date=August 4, 2010}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

A partial census conducted in 1979 showed roughly 15.5 million people living in the country.<ref name="IIOT">{{cite web|url=http://www.gl.iit.edu/govdocs/afghanistan/Afghanistan-Chapter2.pdf |title=Chapter 2. The Society and Its Environment |format=PDF |work=Afghanistan Country Study |publisher=[[Illinois Institute of Technology]]|pages=105<U+2013>06 |accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> The Statistical Yearbook published in 1983 by the [[Babrak Karmal]] government claimed a total population of 15.96 million for 1981<U+2013>82.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/afghanistan/36.htm |title=Population |publisher=U.S. Library of Congress |year=2008 |accessdate=October 12, 2010}}</ref> Between 600,000 to 2 million Afghans were killed during the various 1979<U+2013>2001 wars, majority of them during the Soviet war in the 1980s.<ref name="erols1979"/> At least 5 million more fled the country to neighboring Pakistan and Iran. According to the [[Population Reference Bureau]], the Afghan population is estimated to increase to 82 million by 2050.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prb.org/Countries/Afghanistan.aspx |title=Afghanistan <U+2013> Population Reference Bureau |publisher=[[Population Reference Bureau]] |date= |accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref>

The only city in Afghanistan with over two million residents is its capital, Kabul. The other major cities in the country are, in order of population size, [[Kandahar]], [[Herat]], [[Mazar-e Sharif]], [[Jalalabad]], [[Ghazni]], [[Kunduz]], [[Farah, Afghanistan|Farah]]. Urban areas are experiencing rapid population growth following the return of over 5 million Afghan expats from Pakistan and Iran.

===Ethnic groups===
{{Main|Ethnic groups in Afghanistan}}
[[File:US Army ethnolinguistic map of Afghanistan -- circa 2001-09.jpg|thumb|[[Ethnolinguistics|Ethnolinguistic]] groups of Afghanistan]]
[[File:Khost children in 2010.jpg|thumb|[[Pashtun people|Pashtun]] children from [[Khost Province]]]]
Afghanistan is a [[multiethnic society]]. The population of the country is divided into a wide variety of [[ethnolinguistics|ethnolinguistic]] groups. Because a systematic census has not been held in the nation in decades, exact figures about the size and composition of the various ethnic groups are unvailable.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3717092.stm Afghan poll's ethnic battleground]  October 6, 2004. BBC</ref> In this regard, the [[Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica]] states:{{quote|''No national census has been conducted in Afghanistan since a partial count in 1979, and years of war and population dislocation have made an accurate ethnic count impossible. Current population estimates are therefore rough approximations, which show that Pashtuns comprise somewhat less than two-fifths of the population. The two largest Pashtun tribal groups are the Durrani and Ghilzay. Tajiks are likely to account for some one-fourth of Afghans and Hazara nearly one-fifth. Uzbeks and Chahar Aimaks each account for slightly more than 5 percent of the population and Turkmen an even smaller portion.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/7798/Afghanistan |title=(Ethnic groups) |publisher=Britannica.com |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref>}}
An approximate distribution of the nation's total ethnic groups is shown in the line chart below:

