===Religions===
{{Main|Religion in Afghanistan}}
Over 99% of the Afghan population is Muslim: approximately 80<U+2013>85% follow the [[Sunni Islam|Sunni]] sect, 15<U+2013>19% are [[Shi'a Islam|Shi'a]], and 1% other.<ref name="LoC-pdf">{{cite web|url= http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Afghanistan.pdf |title=Country Profile: Afghanistan |publisher=[[Library of Congress Country Studies]] on Afghanistan |date=August 2008|accessdate=October 10, 2010}}</ref><ref name="PRC">{{cite web|url=http://pewforum.org/Muslim/Mapping-the-Global-Muslim-Population%286%29.aspx |title=Mapping the Global Muslim Population: A Report on the Size and Distribution of the World's Muslim Population|work=[[Pew Research Center]]|publisher=|date=October 7, 2009|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref><ref name="PRCPDF">{{Cite book|url=http://pewforum.org/newassets/images/reports/Muslimpopulation/Muslimpopulation.pdf|title=Mapping the Global Muslim Population: A Report on the Size and Distribution of the World's Muslim Population|editor-last=Miller|editor-first=Tracy |publisher=[[Pew Research Center]] |format=PDF |date = October 2009|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/docs/notesanddefs.html?countryName=Afghanistan&countryCode=af&regionCode=sas#2122 |title=Afghanistan |work=The World Factbook|publisher=[[The World Factbook]] |quote=''Religions: Sunni Muslim 80%, Shia Muslim 19%, other 1%''|accessdate=September 3, 2010}}</ref> Until the 1890s, the region around [[Nuristan Province|Nuristan]] was known as [[Kafiristan]] (land of the [[kafir]]s) because of its inhabitants: the [[Nuristani people|Nuristanis]], an ethnically distinctive people who practiced [[animism]], [[polytheism]] and [[shamanism]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia |last=Klimberg |first=Max |encyclopedia= [[Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Iranica]]|title=NURISTAN |url=http://www.iranica.com/articles/nuristan |edition= Online|date=October 1, 2004 |publisher= Columbia University |location= United States}}</ref> Other than Muslims, there are tiny communities of [[Hinduism in Afghanistan|Hindus]] and [[Sikhs]] found in the four major cities of the country. They number in the thousands.<ref>[http://www.hinduismtoday.com/archives/1994/4/1994-4-02.shtml Hinduism Today: Hindus Abandon Afghanistan].</ref><ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/3138282.stm BBC South Asia: Sikhs struggle in Afghanistan].</ref> There was also a small [[History of the Jews in Afghanistan|Jewish community in Afghanistan]] who emigrated to Israel and the United States by the end of the last century, and only one individual by the name of [[Zablon Simintov]] remains today.<ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A39702-2005Jan26.html Washingtonpost.com <U+2013> Afghan Jew Becomes Country's One and Only <U+2013> N.C. Aizenman].</ref>

==Culture==
{{Main|Culture of Afghanistan}}
[[File:2011 Afghan Youth Voices Festival.jpg|thumb|The 2011 Afghan Youth Voices Festival at the [[Bagh-e Babur|Gardens of Babur]] in the capital Kabul.]]
The [[Culture of Afghanistan|Afghan culture]] has been around for over two millennia, tracing record to at least the time of the Achaemenid Empire in 500 BCE.<ref name="LoC">{{cite web |url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/frd/cs/profiles/Afghanistan.pdf |title=Country Profile: Afghanistan |work=|publisher=[[Library of Congress Country Studies]] on Afghanistan |date = August 2008|accessdate=August 16, 2010}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated5>Barbara Robson, Juliene Lipson, Farid Younos, Mariam Mehdi. {{cite web |url=http://www.cal.org/co/afghan/ahist.html |title=The Afghans <U+2013> Their History and Culture |publisher=[[Center for Applied Linguistics]]|location=United States|date=June 30, 2002|accessdate=September 25, 2010}}</ref> It is mostly a [[nomad]]ic and [[tribal society]], with different regions of the country having their own tradition, reflecting the multi-cultural and multi-lingual character of the nation. In the southern and eastern region, as well as western Pakistan which was historically part of Afghanistan, the people live according to the [[Pashtun culture]] by following [[Pashtunwali]], an ancient lifestyle that is still preserved.<ref>US Library of Congress: Afghanistan <U+2013> [http://lcweb2.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/r?frd/cstdy:@field(DOCID+af0037) Ethnic Groups (''Pashtun'')]</ref> The remaining of the country is culturally [[Persian language|Persian]] and [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]]. Some non-Pashtuns who live in close proximity with Pashtuns have adopted Pashtunwali<ref name="Banting">{{Cite book|title=Afghanistan: The land |last1=Banting|first1=Erinn |authorlink=|coauthors=|volume=|year=2003|publisher=Crabtree Publishing Company |location=|isbn=0778793354|page=32|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=KRt0HfYFZGsC&lpg=PP1&vq=place%20of%20Afghans&pg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=August 22, 2010}}</ref> in a process called [[Pashtunization]] (or ''Afghanization'') while some Pashtuns have been [[Persianization|Persianized]].
[[File:Tribal and religious leaders in southern Afghanistan.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Men wearing their traditional [[Pashtun dress|Afghan dress]] in the ultra-conservative southern city of [[Kandahar]].]]
[[File:Farhad Darya's Peace Concert in 2010-cropped.jpg|thumb|[[Farhad Darya]] performing at the [[Serena Hotel]] in Kabul.]]
Afghans display pride in their culture, nation, ancestry, and above all, their religion and independence. Like other highlanders, they are regarded with mingled apprehension and condescension, for their high regard for personal honor, for their tribe loyalty and for their readiness to use force to settle disputes.<ref name="Heathcote">Heathcote, Tony (1980, 2003) "The Afghan Wars 1839<U+2013>1919", Sellmount Staplehurst.</ref> As tribal warfare and internecine feuding has been one of their chief occupations since time immemorial, this individualistic trait has made it difficult for foreigners to conquer them. Tony Heathcote considers the tribal system to be the best way of organizing large groups of people in a country that is geographically difficult, and in a society that, from a materialistic point of view, has an uncomplicated lifestyle.<ref name="Heathcote" /> There are an estimated 60 major [[Pashtun tribes]],<ref>"[http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/445546/Pashtun Pashtun (people)]". Encyclop<U+00E6>dia Britannica.</ref> and the Afghan nomads are estimated at about 2<U+2013>3 million.<ref>"[http://www.irinnews.org/Report.aspx?ReportId=76794 Afghanistan: Kuchi nomads seek a better deal]". [[IRIN]] Asia. February 18, 2008.</ref>

The nation has a complex history that has survived either in its current cultures or in the form of various languages and monuments. However, many of its historic monuments have been damaged in recent wars.<ref>G.V. Brandolini. ''Afghanistan [[cultural heritage]]''. Orizzonte terra, [[Bergamo]]. 2007. p. 64.</ref> The two famous [[Buddhas of Bamiyan]] were destroyed by the Taliban, who regarded them as [[idolatry|idolatrous]]. Other historical places include the cities of [[Kandahar]], [[Herat]], Ghazni and Balkh. The [[Minaret of Jam]] in the [[Hari River, Afghanistan|Hari River]] valley is a [[World Heritage Site|UNESCO World Heritage site]]. A cloak reputedly worn by Islam's Prophet [[Muhammad]] is stored inside the famous [[Mosque of the Cloak of the Prophet Mohammed]] in Kandahar, a city founded by [[Alexander the Great|Alexander]] and the first capital of Afghanistan. In the city of Herat in the west, the [[citadel]] of Alexander  has been renovated in recent years and is a popular attraction for tourists.

Although literacy level is low, classic [[Persian literature|Persian]] and [[Pashto literature and poetry|Pashto poetry]] play an important role in the Afghan culture. [[Poetry of Afghanistan|Poetry]] has always been one of the major educational pillars in the region, to the level that it has integrated itself into culture. Some notable poets include [[Rumi]], [[Rabi'a Balkhi]], [[Sanai]], [[Jami]], [[Khushal Khan Khattak]], [[Rahman Baba]], [[Khalilullah Khalili]], and [[Parwin Pazhwak]].<ref>[http://www.afghan-web.com/culture/poetry/cpoets.html Classical Dari and Pashto Poets]</ref>

The city of Kabul has been home to many musicians in the past, who were masters of both traditional and modern [[Music of Afghanistan|Afghan music]], especially during the [[Nowruz]] (New Year) and [[Afghan Independence Day|National Independence Day]] celebrations. Most Afghans are accustomed to watching [[Bollywood]] films from India and listening to its [[filmi]] hit songs. Several Bollywood films such as [[Dharmatma]], [[Khuda Gawah]], [[Escape from Taliban]] and [[Kabul Express]] have been shot inside Afghanistan.

Afghans are participants in many kinds of [[sport in Afghanistan|sports]], including soccer, cricket, basketball, volleyball, [[taekwondo]], boxing, and bodybuilding. [[Buzkashi]] is a traditional sport, mainly among the northern Afghans. It is similar to [[polo]], played by horsemen in two teams, each trying to grab and hold a goat carcass. [[Afghan hound]]s (a type of running dog) originated in Afghanistan.{{Citation needed|date=June 2011}}

===Media===
{{Main|Media of Afghanistan}}
The [[Media of Afghanistan|Afghan media]] began in the early 20th century, with the first newspaper published in 1906. By the 1920s, [[Radio Kabul]] was broadcasting local radio services. [[Afghanistan National Television]] was launched in 1974 but was closed in 1996 when the media was tightly controlled by the Taliban.<ref name=dart>Dartnell, M. Y. ''Insurgency Online: Web Activism and Global Conflict.'' University of Toronto Press, 2006. ISBN 978-0-8020-8553-5.</ref> Since 2002, press restrictions were gradually relaxed and private media diversified. [[Freedom of expression]] and the press is promoted in the 2004 constitution and censorship is banned, though [[defamation|defaming]] individuals or producing material contrary to the principles of Islam is prohibited. In 2008, [[Reporters Without Borders]] listed the media environment as 156 out of 173, with 1st being most free. 400 publications are now registered, at least 15 local [[List of television channels in Afghanistan|Afghan television channels]] and 60 radio stations.<ref name=fh>[http://www.freedomhouse.org/template.cfm?page=251&year=2008 Afghanistan Press Report 2008], ''Freedom House''.</ref> Foreign radio stations, such as [[Voice of America]] and [[BBC World Service]], broadcast into the country.

==Health and education==
{{Main|Health in Afghanistan|Education in Afghanistan}}
[[File:Regional Medical Hospital in Paktia.jpg|thumb|upright|Inside a regional [[Afghan National Army|military]] hospital in the [[Paktia Province]]]]
According to the [[Human Development Index]], Afghanistan is the second least developed country in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://hdr.undp.org/en/media/HDR_2009_EN_Complete.pdf |title=UNDP.org |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> Every half hour, an average of one woman dies from pregnancy-related complications, another dies of [[tuberculosis]] and 14 children die, largely from preventable causes. Before the [[Saur Revolution]] in 1978 and the long war that followed, the nation had an improving health system and a semi-modernized [[health care system]] in cities like Kabul. Ibn Sina Hospital and Ali Abad Hospital in Kabul were two of the leading health care institutions in Central Asia at the time.<ref name="reuters.com">{{Cite news|author=Tan Ee Lyn |url=http://www.reuters.com/article/healthNews/idUSISL1059520080506 |title=Afghan medical college struggles to rise from the ashes |publisher=Reuters |date= May 6, 2008|accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> The health care system was limited to urban areas only and was eventually destroyed during the civil war in the early 1990s. The Taliban government made some improvements in the late 1990s, but health care was not available for women during their six year rule.<ref name="reuters.com" /> Afghanistan has one of the highest incidences of people with [[disability|disabilities]] in the world.<ref>"[http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=26520 Afghanistan: People living with disabilities call for integration]". [[IRIN]] Asia. December 2, 2004.</ref> There are an estimated one million disabled or handicapped people in the country.<ref>"[http://www.usaid.gov/stories/afghanistan/fp_afghan_disabled.html Empowering Afghanistan<U+2019>s Disabled Population]". Usaid.gov.</ref> An estimated 80,000 citizens of the country have lost limbs, mainly as a result of landmines.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2008/feb/13/afghanistan Afghanistan's refugee crisis 'ignored']. The Guardian. February 13, 2008.</ref><ref>"[http://www.irinnews.org/report.aspx?reportid=26520 Afghanistan: People living with disabilities call for integration]". [[IRIN]] Asia.</ref>

The nation's health care system began to improve since 2002, which is due to international support on the vaccination of children, training of medical staff. According to USAID, infant mortality rate has dropped by 33 percent and approximately 64 percent of the total population now has access to some form of health care. Most Afghans live within one hour travel to a health facility.<ref name="USAID-Afghanistan-Strategy">{{cite web|url=http://afghanistan.usaid.gov//en/Page.CountryOverview.aspx |title=USAID/Afghanistan Strategy |work=|publisher=[[United States Agency for International Development]] (USAID)|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}{{dead link|date=May 2011}}</ref> Many hospitals and clinics have been built in the country over the last decade, with the most advanced treatments being available in Kabul. The [[French Medical Institute for Children]] and [[Indira Gandhi Childrens Hospital]] in Kabul are the leading [[children's hospital]]s in Afghanistan. The [[Jinnah Hospital]] in Kabul is also under construction, which is funded by the [[Government of Pakistan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.afghanembassyjp.com/en/news/?an=64 |title=Jinnah Hospital to be constructed in Kabul |work=Paktribune|publisher=Embassy of Afghanistan, Tokyo|date=March 7, 2007|accessdate=October 20, 2010}}</ref> There are also a number of well-equipped regional military controlled hospitals across the country that were built by the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] and are run by the [[Afghan National Army]].

Non-governmental charities such as [[Mahboba's promise]] assist orphans in association with governmental structures.<ref>Virginia Haussegger ''Mahooba's Promise'' ABC TV 7.30 Report. 2009. [http://www.abc.net.au/7.30/content/2009/s2615472.htm ABC.net.au]. Retrieved July 15, 2009.</ref> According to [[Reuters]], "Afghanistan's healthcare system is widely believed to be one of the country's success stories since reconstruction began."<ref name="reuters.com" /> However, [[UNICEF]] reported in 2009 that Afghanistan is the most dangerous place in the world for a child to be born.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.oneindia.in/2009/11/20/afghanistan-worst-place-for-children-unicef.html |title=UNICEF on Afghanistan &#124; Worst place &#124; Children Unsafe &#124; Highest Infant Mortality <U+2013> Oneindia News |publisher=News.oneindia.in |date=November 20, 2009 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> The nation has the highest [[infant mortality rate]] in the world <U+2013> 257 deaths per 1,000 live births <U+2013> and 70 percent of the population lacks access to [[clean water]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/india/media_3896.htm |title=UNICEF India <U+2013> Media centre |publisher=Unicef.org |date=January 22, 2008 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paktribune.com/news/print.php?id=222900 |title=Afghanistan world's worst place to be born: UN |publisher=Paktribune.com |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> The [[Ministry of Public Health (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Public Health]] has ambitious plans to cut the infant mortality rate to 400 from 1,600 for every 100,000 live births by 2020.<ref name="reuters.com" /> [[Demographic and Health Surveys]] is working with the [[Indian Institute of Health Management Research]] to conduct a survey in Afghanistan focusing on [[Maternal Mortality]], among other things.<ref name="MEASUREDHS">{{cite web|url=http://www.measuredhs.com/countries/metadata.cfm?surv_id=348&ctry_id=71&SrvyTp=ctry&cn=Afghanistan |title=Afghanistan Surveys |publisher=Measuredhs.com |date= |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref>
[[File:Saleha Bayat Building at AUAF in Kabul-2.jpg|thumb|left|[[American University of Afghanistan]] (AUAF) in Kabul.]]

Education in the country includes [[K<U+2013>12 (education)|K-12]] and Higher, which is supervised by the [[Ministry of Education (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Education]] and [[Ministry of Higher Education (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Higher Education]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mohe.gov.af/?lang=en&p=home |title=Afghanistan's Ministry of Higher Education |accessdate=June 23, 2011}}</ref> The nation's education system fell apart due to the wars after 1978, but it began reviving after the new [[Presidency of Hamid Karzai|Karzai administration]] came to power in late 2001. More than five million male and female students were enrolled in schools as of 2009. However, there are still significant obstacles to education in Afghanistan, stemming from lack of funding, unsafe school buildings and cultural norms. Furthermore, there is a great lack of qualified teachers, especially in rural areas. A lack of women teachers is another issue that concerns some Afghan parents, especially in more conservative areas. Some parents will not allow their daughters to be taught by men.<ref name="asmp">Mojumdar, Aunohita: "Afghan Schools' Money Problems", BBC News, 2007. [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/south_asia/6533379.stm News.BBC.co.uk]</ref> What Afghanistan needs is NATO supported scholarship programs to take massive number of students abroad so that when they return after finishing studies they can move their nation forward and quickly catch up with the rest of the world.

Following the start of the U.S. mission in late 2001, [[Kabul University]] was reopened to both male and female students. In 2006, the [[American University of Afghanistan]] also opened its doors, with the aim of providing a world-class, English-language, co-educational learning environment in Afghanistan. Many other universities were inaugurated across the country in recent years, such as [[Kandahar University]] in the south, [[Herat University]] in the northwest, [[Balkh University]] in the north, [[Nangarhar University]] and [[Khost University]] in the eastern zones, and others. The [[National Military Academy of Afghanistan]] has been set up to train and educate Afghan soldiers.

UNICEF estimates that more than 80 percent of females and around 50 percent of males lack access to education centers. According to the UN, 700 schools have been closed in the country because of poor security.<ref name="chicagotribune.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/chi-tc-nw-afghan-schools-0107jan08,0,457737.story |title=ChicagoTirbune.com |publisher=Chicagotribune.com |date=November 10, 2010 |accessdate=November 14, 2010}}</ref> Literacy of the entire population is estimated at 34%. Female literacy is 10%.<ref name="chicagotribune.com"/> In 2010, the United States began establishing a number of Lincoln learning centers in Afghanistan. They are set up to serve as programming platforms offering English language classes, library facilities, programming venues, Internet connectivity, educational and other counseling services. A goal of the program is to reach at least 4,000 Afghan citizens per month per location.<ref>http://photos.state.gov/libraries/afghanistan/231771/PDFs/RFP-Lincoln-Learning-Centers.pdf</ref><ref>
http://waronterrornews.typepad.com/home/2010/09/ghazni-gov-lincoln-learning-center.html</ref>

==Crime and law enforcement==
{{Main|Crime in Afghanistan|Law enforcement in Afghanistan}}
[[File:ANP moving in vehicles in 2010.jpg|thumb|[[Afghan National Police]]]]
The [[National Directorate of Security]] (NDS) is the nation's domestic [[intelligence agency]], which operates similar to that of the [[United States Department of Homeland Security]] (DHS) and has between 15,000 to 30,000 employees. The nation also has about 126,000 [[Afghan National Police|national police]] officers, with plans to recruit more so that the total number can reach 160,000. The [[Afghan National Police]] (ANP) is under the [[Ministry of Interior (Afghanistan)|Ministry of Interior]] in Kabul, which is headed by [[Bismillah Khan Mohammadi]]. The [[Afghan National Civil Order Police]] is part of the Afghan National Police, which is divided into five Brigades, each commanded by a Brigadier General. These brigades are stationed in Kabul, [[Gardez]], [[Kandahar]], [[Herat]], and [[Mazar-i-Sharif]]. Every province of the country has a provincial [[Chief of Police]] who is appointed by the Ministry of Interior and is responsible for [[law enforcement in Afghanistan|law enforcement]] in all the districts within the province. 

Although they are being trained by [[NATO]] countries and through the [[Afghanistan Police Program]], there are still problems with the force. According to a 2009 news report, large percent of Afghan police officers are illiterate and are accused of demanding bribes.<ref>[http://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=121559123&ps=cprs For U.S., Vast Challenge To Expand Afghan Forces : NPR<!-- Bot generated title -->].</ref> Jack Kem, deputy to the commander of NATO Training Mission Afghanistan and Combined Security Transition Command Afghanistan, stated that the literacy rate in the ANP will reach over 50 percent by January 2012. What began as a voluntary literacy program became mandatory for basic police training in early 2011.<ref name=Pellerindate>{{cite web |url=http://www.defense.gov//news/newsarticle.aspx?id=64044 |title=Afghan Security Forces Grow in Numbers, Quality |publisher=[[United States Department of Defense]] |work=American Forces Press Service |first=Cheryl |last=Pellerindate |date=May 23, 2011 |accessdate=2011-07-10}}</ref> Approximately 17 percent of them test positive for illegal drugs. In 2009, President Karzai created two anti-corruption units within the nation's Interior Ministry.<ref>{{cite web|author=&nbsp; 16 November 2009 |url=http://www1.voanews.com/english/news/a-13-2009-11-16-voa7-70423472.html |title=Afghanistan to Form Major Anti-Corruption Unit &#124; News &#124; English |publisher=.voanews.com |date=November 16, 2009 |accessdate=December 29, 2009}}</ref> Former Interior Minister [[Hanif Atmar]] said that security officials from the U.S. ([[FBI]]), Britain ([[Scotland Yard]]) and the European Union will train prosecutors in the unit.

The south and eastern parts of Afghanistan are the most dangerous due to their distances from Kabul and their flourishing drug trade. These areas in particular are often patrolled by [[Taliban insurgency|Taliban insurgents]], and in many cases they plan attacks by using suicide bombers and planting [[improvised explosive device]]s (IEDs) on roads. Every year [[list of Afghan security forces fatality reports in Afghanistan|many Afghan police officers are killed]] in the line of duty. The [[Afghan Border Police]] are responsible for protecting the nation's airports and borders, especially the [[Durand Line]], which is a disputed border often used by criminal organizations and terrorists for their illegal activities. Reports in 2011 appeared suggesting that up to 3 million people in Afghanistan are involved in the illegal drug business, many of the attacks on government employees and institutions are carried out not only by the Taliban militants but also by powerful criminal gangs.<ref>[http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/20110625/ap_on_re_us/us_us_afghanistan_corruption While US talks withdrawal, Afghan corruption soars], by Bradley Klapper, Associated Press. June 2011.</ref> Drugs from Afghanistan are exported to Iran, Pakistan, Russia, India, the United Arab Emirate, and the European Union. The [[Ministry of Counter Narcotics (Afghanistan)|Afghan Ministry of Counter Narcotics]] which is supported by the international community is dealing with this problem.

==Notes==
{|
|-
|valign="top"|<small>a.{{note label|crown|alternatives|none}}</small>
|valign="top"|Other terms that can be used as demonyms are '''Afghani'''<ref>Dictionary.com. [[The American Heritage Dictionary of the English Language]], Fourth Edition. Houghton Mifflin Company, 2004. [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/afghani Reference.com] (accessed: November 13, 2007).</ref> and '''Afghanistani'''.<ref>Dictionary.com. [[WordNet|WordNet 3.0]]. [[Princeton University]]. [http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/afghanistani Reference.com] (accessed: November 13, 2007).</ref>
|-
|valign="top"|<small>b.{{note label|crown|note|none}}</small>
|valign="top"|The [[Government of India]] also considers Afghanistan to be a bordering country. This is because it considers the entire state of [[Jammu and Kashmir]] to be a part of India including the portion bordering Afghanistan. A ceasefire sponsored by the UN in 1948 froze the positions of Indian and Pakistani-held territory. As a consequence, the region bordering Afghanistan is in [[Pakistan-administered Kashmir]].
|}

